The RBMK reactor, or roughly translated to "high-power channel type reactor" is a Soviet designed graphite moderated and light water cooled reactor. This type of reactor is not found in any other country in the world and thus has some unique characteristics. It was designed this way to allow the use of the un-enriched Uranium (Uranium-238, the more stable isotope that doesn't fission) as its fuel which is much cheaper.

Because the RBMK reactor is both graphite moderated and light water cooled it comes with the property called the positive void coefficient. Typically reactors use light water as both a moderator and a coolant and have instead a negative void coefficient. This comes from the fact that, as water turns to steam, it becomes much less effective as a moderator thus reducing radioactivity. However in a RMBK reactor, when it uses light water as a coolant, when the water turns into steam, it becomes a much less effective absorber thus creating a increase in radioactivity. This positive void coefficient becomes a vicious cycle of increase in radioactivity  -> increase of heat -> increase in steam, etc.

One last factor in maintaining the balance of an RBMK reactor is the fuel temperature coefficient. This coefficient describes how, when the temperature of the fuel increases, the reactivity decreases. This is because as the fuel heats up the atoms vibrate more and this motion actually effects the motion of the neutrons effectively halting the fission rate. This is the delicate dance that is done in a RBMK reactor. As shown by the figure below.
